<div class="container page-container">
    <h1>Variables: Naming and Storing Information</h1>
    <BR>
        <BR>
    <p>
        Variables are the fundamental components for storing and managing data in any computer program. They are essentially <strong>reserved spots in your computer's memory</strong> that hold a specific type of information.
    </p>
    <p>
        Think of a variable like a <strong>labeled post-it note</strong> that you stick onto a file cabinet drawer: the <strong>label</strong> is the <strong>variable name</strong> (<code>score</code>), the <strong>drawer type</strong> is the <strong>variable type</strong> (<code>int</code>, <code>string</code>), and the <strong>information written</strong> is the <strong>value</strong> (<code>100</code>).
    </p>

    <hr />

    <h2>Creating a Variable: Declaration and Assignment</h2>
    <p>When you use a variable, you generally follow two steps:</p>
    <BR>

    <h3>1. Declaration (Naming the Spot)</h3>
    <p>You tell the computer the <strong>type</strong> of information you will store and what <strong>name</strong> you want to call it.</p>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Syntax Example</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre style="white-space: pre-wrap;">
int score;      // Tells the computer to save a spot for an integer named 'score'.
string message; // Saves a spot for a string named 'message'.
</pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h3>2. Assignment / Initialization (Putting the Value In)</h3>
    <p>This is when you put the first value into the variable or change it later using <strong>=</strong>, which means assignment.</p>
    <p>Most often, we combine these steps into one line, called <strong>Initialization</strong>.</p>

    <hr />

    <h2>📋 Extended Types of Variables (Data Types)</h2>
    <p>The data type is crucial because it tells the computer how to manage the data. Here are the core types:</p>

    <table class="table table-bordered">
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>Data Type</th>
                <th>What It Stores</th>
                <th>Example Value</th>
                <th>Notes</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>int</strong></td>
                <td><strong>Whole numbers</strong></td>
                <td><code>15</code>, <code>-200</code></td>
                <td>Used for counts, age, and scores.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>float</strong></td>
                <td><strong>Decimal numbers</strong></td>
                <td><code>3.14</code>, <code>1.5</code></td>
                <td>Requires <code>f</code> suffix in C#.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>char</strong></td>
                <td><strong>A single character</strong></td>
                <td><code>'A'</code>, <code>'$'</code></td>
                <td>Only holds one symbol.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>string</strong></td>
                <td><strong>Words or sentences</strong></td>
                <td><code>"Hello"</code>, <code>"Anna"</code></td>
                <td>Used for text.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>bool</strong></td>
                <td><strong>true/false</strong></td>
                <td><code>true</code>, <code>false</code></td>
                <td>Used for yes/no states.</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

    <hr />

    <h2>💻 Complete Code Examples</h2>

    <div class="form-check form-switch mb-3">
        <input class="form-check-input" type="checkbox" id="languageToggle" onchange="convertCode()">
        <label class="form-check-label" for="languageToggle">Convert to C#</label>
    </div>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Code Example (C++)</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre id="codeBlock" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">
// Initializing variables (Declaration + Assignment)
int age = 13;
float height = 1.55;
char grade = 'A';
string name = "Alex";
bool hasLicense = false;

// Using variables in an operation
int yearBorn = 2025 - age;

// Outputting the result (Conceptually)
// print("Alex was born in: " + yearBorn);
</pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p>In this example, the computer uses the value stored in <strong>age</strong> to calculate <strong>yearBorn</strong>.</p>

    <h3>Changing the Value (Re-Assignment)</h3>
    <p>Since variables are designed to <strong>vary</strong>, you can update them anytime:</p>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Code Example</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre style="white-space: pre-wrap;">
// Original values from above...
age = 15;
name = "Anna";

hasLicense = true;
</pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p><strong>Fun Example:</strong></p>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Game Stats</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre style="white-space: pre-wrap;">
string userName = "TheCoder7";
int healthPoints = 100;
float speed = 5.5;
bool isAlive = true;
</pre>
        </div>
    </div>

